Take. The. Risk.

Okay maybe you don’t have to move across the country, or leave everyone and everything you’ve ever known. But what if you did something different this year?

What if this was the year you stopped letting fear dictate your decisions?

What if this was the year you stopped worrying what everyone else thinks and worried about what YOU thought more?

Let this year be a pivotal year for you. Because you don’t want to spend a lifetime wondering, what if?

I caught myself doing something recently…

& it’s something I talk about often.

Something I talk about avoiding.

I caught myself comparing.

Comparing with motherhood, with my business, with creating content - basically all the things. And I was spiraling and then found myself paralyzed from wanting to move forward with anything.

And over the years, with so much inner work, I’ve been able to catch myself. I’ve been able to stop that thinking, rewire my thoughts with something positive, proactive, and productive. But lately I’ve been struggling to do that.

But somehow I feel like I’m coming out on the other side of it. Between getting outside, confiding in loved ones, and simply honoring where I’m at and celebrating that - I’ve stopped the spiral.

I wanted to share this. Because I know how easy it can be to get caught in the trap. And you know the quote, “comparison is the thief of joy”? It’s freaking true. You are uniquely YOU and that is the most amazing thing. If you’re finding yourself in a similar place that I was: have a good vent session, journal, get outside, and refocus in on the things that matter to YOU. Because that’s the only person who matters 👏🏼

I remember seeing a coworker in tears.

Her child was sick. They needed to go to the doctor. It wasn’t even lunch yet. She was scrambling to find a sub, make sure her students would be okay, all while being worried sick about her baby at home.

It was in that moment I knew that when I became a mom one day, I wanted to be there. For the sick days, the good days, and every day in between. But I also knew I wanted something MORE.

I already had started my business on the side, but seeing that made me realize I wanted to level up. I wanted to make it into more than just a side business all because of the “one day I want to be home with my babies” idea tugging at my heart.

I’ve worked really freaking hard for days like today and I’m insanely proud. But even more proud that I have the honor of mentoring other women who want to do the same. Who want to be home with their babies while still creating more for their lives. It’s so much bigger than just me.

Mama- there is nothing wrong if you love what you do outside of the house. But I know there’s someone out there like me who wanted this. A normal Wednesday afternoon spent with their babe. And if that’s you…let’s talk 🫶🏼

It’s no longer just for me.

My story isn’t about the girl who played sports growing up. Or who loved going to studio classes. Or who enjoyed getting sweaty or sore.

It wasn’t until the key shifts were made for me: a simple structure I could follow and stick to. Variety to keep things fresh. And a group to hold me accountable and help me work on my mindset AND nutrition.

Maybe you’ve heard me say this before.

I was not/am not an athlete. I actually used to come up with ANY excuse to avoid going to the gym with my friends, or participating in any kind of sport. Come play volleyball? No…I can’t I have to walk my neighbors dog…

As I grew up, I learned how important it was to take care of your body. So I tried going to a gym - insert me hiding in the corner looking up pinterest workouts. Then I tried going to studio classes - catch me in the back of the class or frustrated because I couldn’t make it to a class before they filled up before/after work. I felt like I was totally that person who was “on and off the wagon” over and over, and it was exhausting.

I started to tell myself - this is just how it’s going to be for your whole life. You were never an athlete so why would health and wellness come easy to you? 

Here’s the thing - it would never come “easy” to me BUT I’ve learned to absolutely love the process of working on myself and my health and wellness over these last 6 years. And the thing is- it doesn’t get easier, you just get stronger.

But to now have had these programs take me through every important phase of my life? Prepping for my wedding? Moving across the country? A healthy pregnancy? Now an example for my daughter? That’s absolutely priceless. 

And did you know that it all started with a 3 week program? It laid the foundation for my fitness, mindset & nutrition. I documented every dang day of that program. You want proof? Scroll to the beginning of this Instagram 😅 I needed this virtual accountability here and in the wellness studio. Because like I said - it wasn’t easy for me. 

We may be on different chapters in our health and wellness journeys - but I want you to know that you don’t have to keep telling yourself the same story that I was. You don’t have to keep feeling stuck and like this is the way it has to be forever. You can rewrite your story just like I did. One day at a time. 

If you want details on the test group I’m putting together (for the revamped program I got started with 6 years ago), you know I’m just one message away.

I tried for a while to hang onto the “old” me. 

For the first 3-4 months I felt this weird pull, shift and identity crisis that I think a lot of new moms go through. But after the newness of motherhood started to wear down, I realized something:

I love being a mom.

Like I was made for this. I love the little moments. Even the hard days, the exhausting days, the trying times. I find joy in it all. I wouldn’t trade these days for the world. I know my beautiful girl is only little for a short time, so I consciously work on being present and embracing this short chapter…my favorite chapter.

Im in my motherhood era and I am here for it 👏🏼 anyone else?

Stop overcomplicating it.

& it’s clear that what you tell yourself matters. So my friend, if you’re just getting started…I want you to know these things:

1️⃣Learn to rest not quit: it’s okay to slow down or for your routines and schedule to look different than someone else’s. Just because you have an off day (or few days) doesn’t mean you have to “start all over” again. Get right back to it!

2️⃣Focus on your mindset: what you tell yourself matters!! If you’re only focusing on the negative and what isn’t going right, that’s what you’ll continue to see. Celebrate every small milestone and keep the thoughts positive. One step at a time. 

3️⃣Enjoy prepping meals with whole ingredients: I hear this all the time from my clients, “I’m not good at cooking/meal prepping”. Go back to step 2 and flip that and add in the word YET. It’s probably because it’s new to you! Start small. Focus on proteins, veggies, fiber filled carbs, and healthy fats! Prep 1-2 meals or snacks for your week and build from there.

4️⃣Find a supportive community: this was the game changer. I had to stop trying to do this by myself. There’s nothing wrong with getting some accountability from other like minded women!

5️⃣Fall in love with the process: it’s not a one and done for an event or season…it’s your health and wellness for LIFE. So let’s fall in love with the journey of it all- the highs and the lows. Deal?

Sorry, Ken. You’re stuck with me.

I got cut from the 8th grade volleyball team.

I’ll never forget it because that was when I decided sports weren’t for me. I cried. I felt embarrassed. I felt like I wasn’t good enough. (Granted, I did play tennis in high school…but I wasn’t very good 😅)

What followed was a decade of telling myself the same story over and over: I’m not athletic. Which then translated into me struggling to find joy in exercise.

Somehow, I equated athleticism (and coordination lol) with enjoying consistently working out and taking care of my physical health.

If I could go back and talk to my 8th grade self, I’d tell her that you don’t have to be athletic to take care of yourself. That it doesn’t have to be that one way or nothing at all. That you can find ways to take care of yourself that might look different than what others are doing.

& I know for sure that’s what I’ll be telling Kennedy- or rather, I’ll be showing her. Leading by example for my girl every single day. Do we absolutely joke that we hope she gets her dads athletic abilities? Absolutely 😅 maybe she’ll be the soccer star. But if one day, she gets cut from the team, you better believe her mindset will be so solid from watching her mom all these years.

So please- if you’re telling yourself some story about the things you “aren’t” but wish you were…let’s talk my friend. You don’t have to stay in this place.

Ingredients:

- Optional toppings: grated part, fresh basil

- Serve with grated parmesan cheese and enjoy!

Okay maybe just a mom’s sanity 😅 but honestly it’s crucial for my week to go smoothly no matter how small the prep. A little bit can go a long way!

Once I finally came out of the newborn fog, I started prepping slowly but surely. Then when Kennedy started eating solids, I shifted to only prepping for her. Now I’ve evolved into entire family prep! I tell you all of this because it’s okay if your prep goes in waves too. But I promise if you give it a go, take the time to get in your flow, you’re going to love the freedom it gives your week!

My top tips for family meal prepping:
1️⃣ PLAN! Sit down over the weekend and plan out some meals. I personally plan breakfasts for the fam, snacks for Kennedy, lunches for me, and 2 dinners because I’ll make enough for leftovers. Write everything down and take inventory of what you’ve got in your fridge and pantry.

2️⃣BATCH COOK! Meaning- cook in bulk! I chopped all 6 of my peppers to roast so it will last me multiple days. Prepare your staples like quinoa, pasta, sweet potatoes, roasted veggies, etc. this saves time and obviously reduces the need for daily cooking!

3️⃣EVERYONE EATS THE SAME! One of the best things I did when Kennedy started eating solids was including her to eat what we eat. I didn’t want to double cook, so it took some tweaking to find what was best for our family.

4️⃣INCLUDE THE FAM! Have something to grill for the week? Rope your husband in and have him grill extra for the week ahead. Your little one wants to be involved? Give them some utensils to help mix, or help them dump things in. Sure, this might take extra time but they’ll love helping.Z

5️⃣START SMALL! It doesn’t have to be perfect. Just starting and learning as you go is a huge part of it.
